msContents.summary: Fair copy of the 1622 edition of a work written in 1567 on assaying gold and silver. The discussion of assaying includes the first known observation that tin and lead gain weight upon heating during calcinations. Information on management of the mint is also included. An alphabetical index (Register) follows the text (p. 233-241).

supportDesc.extent: 135 leaves : 203 x 155 (162 x 125) mm. bound to 203 x 160 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, ii + 135 + i leaves; [i-xxviii], 1-232, [233-242]. Catchwords on each page, lower right corner.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 21-22 long lines; outer vertical margins marked by folding.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a German cursive script by a single hand.

binding.p: Contemporary 17th-century marbled paper with Modestin Fachsen, Probier Büch, MDLXVII written in ink on upper cover; blue paper spine with Modestin Fachsen, Probier Büchlein, 1622, 1567 written in ink on spine label. A call number, XXI.171, was later added outside and inside the upper cover.

origin.p: Written in Germany in the second half of the 17th century.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by bookseller and mineral dealer Joseph A. Freilich (Bayville, N.Y.; bookplate, inside upper cover).
Sold at auction as part of the Freilich collection at Sotheby's, 10 Jan. 2001, lot 181, to Lawrence J. Schoenberg.
Deposit by Lawrence J. Schoenberg and Barbara Brizdle, 2011.
